Preliminary Data Exploration¶

Explore the data set before determining the project topic. The goal of the preliminary data exploration is to explore interesting aspects of the data set, and develop potential project ideas.

The preliminary data exploration step aim to answer the following questions:

a) Can you identify any limitations or distortions of the data?

b) What is the most popular name of all time? (Of either gender.)

c) What is the most gender ambiguous name in 2013? 1945?

d) Of the names represented in the data, find the name that has had the largest percentage increase in popularity since 1980. Largest decrease?

e) Can you identify names that may have had an even larger increase or decrease in popularity?

Basic Data Description¶

There are two datasets on Kaggle. The first one is the national names dataset. This dataset contains 5 columns, which are ID, name, year, gender, and count. The total number of observations is 1825432. The range of the year is from 1880 to 2014. The range of the frequency of each name in each year is from 5 to 99680. And there are in total 93889 unique names recorded on our database.

Data Exploration¶

Identify any limitation or distortions of the data:

Identification of data limitations and distortions We begin our data exploration by first look at possible data limitations and distortions. The very first step we think about is the missing value issue. Then we the sanity check by firstly look at the potential missing values. After the checking, we found that there is no missing value on each column of the data. The second issue that we concerned about is the trend of the total observations collected along years. Then we grouped by the variable year and drew a line graph and the results are presented in fig.1. There is an obvious increasing trend over time from 1880 to 2014. But since 2010, there is a slight decreasing trend.

The years included in the national data set and the state data set do not match up. The national data begins in 1880 while the state data begins in 1910. There is a different number of names for each row and for each state because the criteria used for including the name in the data set is that the name has to have a minimum of five occurrences. Thus we cannot assume that the number of names in the data set will be the same for any two years.

Gender Irregularity

The next issue that we are digging into is that whether there are some female or male names appear irregularly in the dataset. For example, we want to check whether there are some names that have the high frequency among the female population but also has very high frequency in the male population. This time we just did a very early stage data exploration. We took 1880 as an example and calculated the frequency of each name in 1880 and calculated the frequency of each names appeared among female and male populations. And take the females as an example. We found that there seems to be no obvious irregular names appears. Because the names appear to have high frequencies among females all have very low frequencies on males. The method we want to check whether the name should be a female name or a male name is to draw the number of the name appears versus the time in males and females. Take the name Olivia as an example. This name does not seem to have very high frequency among female names. But as time goes by, the number of females with name Olivia increased a lot but very little increase in males. So we can conclude that Olivia is the common name among female but not a common name among males. Please refer to fig 2 and fig 3. But if there does appear to be some names that has both high frequencies in males and females, we should think that whether this name is a common name that could be used by both females and males or it may be due to the mislabel of the gender categories.

Popular Name

Most popular names Then we look the most popular names from 1880 to 2014. Regardless of gender, the most popular names are James and John. For females, the most popular names are Mary and Elizabeth. For males, the top 2 are also James and John. Clearly, there is a distinction between female popular names and male popular names. But surprisingly, the populars name of all gender is pretty similar to the popular names of male. It is probably because we have more males than female in our data set.

Most Ambigous Name across all the time: We define the ambigous as "cannot distinguish the gender by name". Thus, if the name having high counts in both gender (50-50 chance in both gender), we regard it as high ambiguity. If the name is used only for male or only for female, we regard it as low ambiguity. If order to find the ambiguity accurately, we would like to filter out the name with too low number of total count. For example, if there is a name have only two count, one for female and one for male. Based on the criteria we set before, we will regard it as high ambigous name, but only two count may not sufficient to show the name is a ambigous name.

Here, we measure the ambiguity by calculating the ambiguity ratio. We then look at the ambiguity of names in 2013 and 1945. The most gender ambiguous name is Artie in 1945 and Arie in 2013.

Most gender ambiguous name in 2013

In [505]:
def ambiguous(year):
    name_gender_count_year = df[df['Year']==year]
    name_count_year = df[df['Year']==year].groupby(['Name']).agg({'Count':'sum'})
    name_count_year = name_count_year.reset_index()
    comb_year = name_gender_count_year.merge(name_count_year, on = 'Name')
    both_gender_year = comb_year[comb_year['Count_x']!=comb_year['Count_y']]
    both_gender_year = both_gender_year[both_gender_year['Count_y'] >= 100]
    both_gender_year.loc[:, 'gender_ratio'] = both_gender_year['Count_x']/both_gender_year['Count_y']
    both_gender_year.loc[:, 'ambig_ratio'] = 0.5 - abs(both_gender_year['gender_ratio'] - 0.5)
    sort_ambig_year = both_gender_year.sort(['ambig_ratio','Count_y', 'Name'], ascending=False)
    sort_ambig_year = sort_ambig_year[['Name', 'Gender', 'Count_x', 'Count_y', 'ambig_ratio']]
    sort_ambig_year.columns = ['Name', 'Gender', 'Count_Each', 'Total_Count', 'Ambigous_Ratio']
    return sort_ambig_year
